# =============================================================================
# Caddyfile — Cognitive Avatar Protocol Gateway Configuration
# =============================================================================
#
# Gateway Routing Rules Documentation
# ====================================
#
# This Caddyfile configures the reverse proxy gateway for the Cognitive Avatar
# Protocol. It listens on port 81 (mapped to 80/443 in production via Docker)
# and routes traffic to the appropriate backend services.
#
# ── Routing Logic ───────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# 1. Default Route (no XTransformPort query parameter):
#    → All requests are forwarded to the Next.js app on port 3000
#    → This includes: HTML pages, API routes (/api/*), static assets
#
# 2. XTransformPort Query Parameter:
#    → When a request includes ?XTransformPort=<port>, Caddy reads the
#      port number and reverse-proxies to localhost:<port>
#    → This enables the Next.js frontend to communicate with microservices
#      through the same gateway without CORS issues
#
# ── Port Mapping ────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Port  Service            Description
# ────  ─────────────────  ───────────────────────────────────────
# 3000  app                Next.js main application (App Router)
# 3003  resonance-sim      Socket.IO resonance simulation service
# 3004  monitoring-sim     Socket.IO monitoring simulation service
# 3005  ifd-calculator     IFD (Fluid Democracy) calculation engine
# 3006  ece-oracle         ECE (Emotional Consensus Engine) oracle
# 3007  poue-prover        POUE (Proof of Understanding) prover engine
# 3008  mcp-router         MCP (Model Context Protocol) router
#
# ── WebSocket Support ──────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Caddy natively supports WebSocket upgrades. No special configuration
# is needed beyond the reverse_proxy directive. Socket.IO connections
# from the frontend use the path:
#
#   /?XTransformPort=3003  (resonance-sim)
#   /?XTransformPort=3004  (monitoring-sim)
#
# The frontend MUST use:
#   io("/?XTransformPort=3003")  — CORRECT
#   io("http://localhost:3003")  — PROHIBITED (bypasses gateway)
#
# ── CORS Headers ───────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# The reverse_proxy directive forwards the following headers:
# - Host: Preserved from original request
# - X-Forwarded-For: Client IP address
# - X-Forwarded-Proto: Original scheme (http/https)
# - X-Real-IP: Client real IP address
#
# CORS headers are handled by the backend services themselves, not
# by Caddy. Each Socket.IO service configures its own CORS settings
# to allow connections from the app origin.
#
# ── Production Considerations ──────────────────────────────────
#
# In production, the Caddyfile should be extended to:
# 1. Replace :81 with the production domain (e.g., cognitive-avatar.protocol)
# 2. Add TLS configuration (Caddy auto-provisions via Let's Encrypt)
# 3. Add rate limiting and request size limits
# 4. Add compression (gzip/brotli) for non-WebSocket responses
# 5. Add security headers (X-Frame-Options, CSP, etc.)
# 6. Add logging configuration
#
# Example production block:
#
#   cognitive-avatar.protocol {
#       @transform_port_query {
#           query XTransformPort=*
#       }
#       handle @transform_port_query {
#           reverse_proxy localhost:{query.XTransformPort}
#       }
#       handle {
#           reverse_proxy localhost:3000
#       }
#       encode gzip
#       header {
#           X-Frame-Options DENY
#           X-Content-Type-Options nosniff
#           Referrer-Policy strict-origin-when-cross-origin
#       }
#       log {
#           output file /var/log/caddy/access.log
#       }
#   }
#
# =============================================================================

:81 {
        # ── Route: XTransformPort query parameter ──────────────
        # When the URL contains ?XTransformPort=<port>, forward
        # the request to the specified microservice port.
        @transform_port_query {
                query XTransformPort=*
        }

        handle @transform_port_query {
                reverse_proxy localhost:{query.XTransformPort} {
                        header_up Host {host}
                        header_up X-Forwarded-For {remote_host}
                        header_up X-Forwarded-Proto {scheme}
                        header_up X-Real-IP {remote_host}
                }
        }

        # ── Default Route: Next.js App ────────────────────────
        # All other requests go to the main Next.js application.
        handle {
                reverse_proxy localhost:3000 {
                        header_up Host {host}
                        header_up X-Forwarded-For {remote_host}
                        header_up X-Forwarded-Proto {scheme}
                        header_up X-Real-IP {remote_host}
                }
        }
}
